New research in an area of the Scottish Highlands is looking to reveal how bats use the landscape in their quest for food.
It is hoped that the observations will shed new light on the behavior of these unique flying mammals and guide future conservation activities.
Researchers from the National Trust for Scotland will follow common bats and sopranos as well as long-eared brown bats and Daubenton at the Inverewe Garden in Wester Ross.
Special recording devices will be placed in key locations around the property in order to track the activity of bats throughout the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile surveys using portable detectors.
A professional sound analysis will help to determine the frequency of cries of bats as well as the activities of the different species.
A map and habitat report will be drawn up to provide a detailed map of their territorial behaviour.
Rob Dewar, Nature Conservation Advisor for the NTS, hopes that the results will reveal the most important habitat areas for bats and how they are used by each of these species.
This information will determine the benefits of habitat management work such as grassland creation and the best way to conserve forests for bats and other related species.
In Scotland and the United Kingdom, bat populations have declined considerably over the past century.
They are threatened by construction and development works that affect the perchors and result in the loss of their habitat.
Wind turbines and lighting can also pose a risk, as can fly-killing papers and certain chemical treatments of building materials, as well as pet cat attacks.
Mosquitoes are not really blind.
