Europe wins the Ryder Cup in Paris
The European team won the 2018 Ryder Cup by beating the U.S. team with a final score of 16.5 to 10.5 at Golf National near Paris, France.
The United States has now lost six times in a row on European soil and has not won a Ryder Cup in Europe since 1993.
Europe regained the title when the team of Danish captain Thomas Bjorn crossed the bar of the 14.5 points needed to beat the United States.
American star Phil Mickelson, who was in trouble during most of the tournament, plunged his starting shot into the water at the 16th hole in par-3, surrendering his duel to Francesco Molinari.
Italian golfer Molinari excelled in all his rounds, becoming one of four players to have ever reached 5-0-0 since the current format of the tournament, whose first edition dates back to 1979.
American Jordan Spieth was knocked out 5 to 4 by the European team's lowest-placed player, Thorbjorn Olesen, from Denmark.
The best golfer in the world, Dustin Johnson, tilted 2 and 1 against Englishman Ian Poulter, who may have played his last Ryder Cup.
A veteran of eight Ryder Cups, Spanish Sergio Garcia has become the European champion of all time with a total of 25.5 career points.
