Red tide info point: Lower concentrations in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report by the Florida Fisheries and Wildlife Commission indicates a general decrease in red tidal concentrations in certain areas of the Tampa Bay region.
According to the CPF, more irregular flowering conditions are reported in the areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties - which is feared by declining concentrations.
The red tide covers approximately 209 km (130 miles) of coastline, from northern Pinellas to southern Lee counties.
There are islands about 16 km (10 miles) off Hillsborough County, but in fewer sites than last week.
The red tide was also observed in Pasco County.
Moderate concentrations in or outside Pinellas County have been reported last week, low to high concentrations outside Hillsborough County, higher concentrations in Manatee County, higher concentrations at the bottom of Sarasota County or overseas, wide to high concentrations in Collotte County, and low concentrations at low concentrations.
Cases of respiratory irritation persist in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
No respiratory irritation has been reported in northwest Florida over the past week.
